            ">Eleventh hour push</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/ps-dec-18-1.png" alt="Eleventh hour push" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">TikTok and its parent company ByteDance have filed an <a href="https://amp.theguardian.com/technology/2024/dec/16/tiktok-ban-supreme-court" target="_blank">emergency appeal</a> to the US Supreme Court to block a law forcing ByteDance to divest TikTok by January 19 or face a nationwide ban. They argue the law violates First Amendment <a href="https://www.uscourts.gov/about-federal-courts/educational-resources/about-educational-outreach/activity-resources/what-does-free-speech-mean" target="_blank">free speech</a> protections, as TikTok is a central platform used by 170 million Americans. They claim the ban would harm free expression and cause irreparable economic damage, including loss of users, advertisers, and creators.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Some US government officials view TikTok as a national security risk. The main concerns are over ByteDance’s access to sensitive user data and potential content manipulation, which TikTok denies. The appeal comes as <a href="https://time.com/6900348/tiktok-ban-donald-trump-congress/" target="_blank">Donald Trump</a>, who previously sought to ban the app, now supports it. To avoid disruptions, a ruling has been requested by January 6.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Carbon monoxide poisoning in Georgia</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/ps-dec-18-2.png" alt="Carbon monoxide poisoning in Georgia" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Eleven Indian nationals and one Georgian were found <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/georgia-11-indians-found-dead-at-gudauri-ski-resort/a-71081207" target="_blank">dead</a> at a <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Gudauri,+Georgia/@42.4758858,44.4611023,15z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m10!1m2!2m1!1sgudauri+ski+resort!3m6!1s0x404528fdf2ee8197:0xf2c31d07053611a4!8m2!3d42.4755394!4d44.4804723!15sChJndWRhdXJpIHNraSByZXNvcnSSAQhsb2NhbGl0eeABAA!16zL20vMDhyajJw?entry=ttu&g_ep=EgoyMDI0MTIxMS4wIKXMDSoASAFQAw%3D%3D" target="_blank">Gudauri</a> ski resort in Georgia, reportedly due to suspected carbon monoxide poisoning. The victims, believed to be workers at an Indian restaurant, were discovered in a commercial building where an oil-powered generator had been turned on following a power outage. Authorities indicated that the generator was placed dangerously close to an indoor area, accumulating carbon monoxide.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          The Indian embassy in Tbilisi expressed deep condolences and assured it is working with local authorities to repatriate the victims' remains to India. The embassy also contacts the bereaved families to provide necessary support. Preliminary investigations found no signs of violence, and officials continued to assess the incident to confirm the exact cause of death.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="              
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Extradition request rejected</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Denmark has <a href="https://www.rcinet.ca/eye-on-the-arctic/2024/12/17/canadian-anti-whaling-activist-wont-be-extradited-to-face-japanese-charges/" target="_blank">rejected</a> Japan's request to extradite anti-whaling activist Paul Watson, founder of the Sea Shepherd group and Captain Paul Watson Foundation, over charges stemming from a 2010 incident in the Antarctic Ocean. Watson, 74, had been detained in Greenland since July when his ship docked there, but he was released after the decision.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The Danish justice ministry said the age of the case and uncertainty over whether Watson's detention time in Greenland would count toward a potential Japanese sentence. Watson's lawyer, Julie Stage, welcomed the outcome, stressing Watson's composure throughout the process. Japan had sought Watson on charges including trespassing, obstruction, and causing injury, which he denies. He had a list of high-profile supporters ranging from the French President <a href="https://www.lemonde.fr/en/france/article/2024/07/23/macron-presses-against-anti-whaling-activist-s-extradition_6695602_7.html" target="_blank">Emmanuel Macron</a>, Brigitte Bardot, and Pierce Brosnan petitioning for his release. After residing in France since 2023, Watson left Sea Shepherd in 2022 to form his conservation organization.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
   
